scenarios.answer:
## 🔥 The situation

You need to add a feature to a service that has zero tests. Any line you change could break something — SQL quirks, hidden assumptions, side effects in constructors.

The fear is real. Without tests, you do not know what the code is supposed to do.

---

## 🧠 Key insight — production IS the spec

In legacy code, there are no unit tests to tell you what the code should do.
But there is one source of truth: **what the code actually does in production right now**.

Your job: capture that behavior in tests BEFORE you change anything.

---

## Step 1: Build a risk map — what must never break

Before writing any code, list the things that would hurt most if they broke:

| Risk level | Examples | Your priority |
|---|---|---|
| 🔴 Critical | Payments, login, PII, inventory | Test first, flag everything |
| 🟡 Important | Order flow, subscriptions | Cover before you touch |
| 🟢 Lower | Admin reports, internal dashboards | Lower blast radius |

**Why this matters:** You do not need 100% coverage. You need deep coverage around the **code you are about to change**.

---

## Step 2: Capture baseline metrics — before you touch anything

**Run this or check your monitoring dashboard:**
```bash
# Check current error rate for endpoints you will touch
curl "http://grafana/api/datasources/proxy/1/api/v1/query?query=rate(http_server_requests_seconds_count{uri='/api/orders',status='5xx'}[5m])"
```

**What you want to see before starting:**
```text
Error rate: 0.02%   ← record this number
p99 latency: 180ms  ← record this number
```

**Why:** After your change, you compare to these numbers. If error rate goes up, you broke something.

---

## Step 3: Write a characterization test — lock current behavior

A characterization test captures what the code does TODAY — even if it is wrong. It prevents your refactor from accidentally changing behavior.

```java
// You found this method in legacy code. You do not fully understand it.
// Write a test that locks its current output BEFORE you change it.
@Test
void legacyDiscountCalculation_matchesTodaysBehavior() {
    LegacyPricer pricer = new LegacyPricer();

    // Run it with known input
    BigDecimal result = pricer.calculate("GOLD", 100.0, 3);

    // Lock current output — even if you think it might be wrong
    // This is your safety net during refactoring
    assertThat(result).isEqualByComparingTo("85.50");
}
```

**What happens when this test runs:**
```text
Tests run: 1, Failures: 0, Errors: 0, Skipped: 0
BUILD SUCCESS
```

**Now if you accidentally change the output during refactoring:**
```text
Expected: 85.50
 but was: 90.00
BUILD FAILED  ← test caught your mistake ✅
```

**For DB code — use real database, not mocks:**
```java
@SpringBootTest
@Testcontainers  // spins up a real PostgreSQL in Docker
class OrderRepositoryTest {

    @Container
    static PostgreSQLContainer<?> db = new PostgreSQLContainer<>("postgres:15");

    @Test
    void findByCustomer_returnsOrdersInDateOrder() {
        // Test against real SQL — catches quirks mocks miss
        List<Order> orders = repo.findByCustomerId(42L);
        assertThat(orders).isSortedAccordingTo(Comparator.comparing(Order::getCreatedAt));
    }
}
```

**What you see when Testcontainers starts:**
```text
🐳 Pulling image: postgres:15
🐳 Container started in 3.2s
✅ Tests run: 1, Failures: 0
```

---

## Step 4: Add a seam — make your new code testable and replaceable

A seam is a boundary you introduce so you can test and replace parts independently.

**Before — HTTP call buried inside business logic (impossible to test or change):**
```java
public BigDecimal calculatePrice(Order order) {
    // ❌ Hardcoded HTTP call — cannot test without real server
    TaxRate rate = new HttpClient().get("https://tax-api.com/rate/" + order.getCountry());
    return order.getAmount().multiply(rate.getValue());
}
```

**After — inject the dependency (now you can test each part):**
```java
public BigDecimal calculatePrice(Order order, TaxRateProvider taxProvider) {
    // ✅ taxProvider can be a real HTTP call in production
    //    or a simple test double in tests
    TaxRate rate = taxProvider.getRate(order.getCountry());
    return order.getAmount().multiply(rate.getValue());
}

// In your test:
@Test
void calculatePrice_appliesTaxCorrectly() {
    TaxRateProvider fakeTax = country -> new TaxRate(0.20); // no HTTP needed
    BigDecimal price = service.calculatePrice(order, fakeTax);
    assertThat(price).isEqualByComparingTo("120.00");
}
```

---

## Step 5: Ship behind a feature flag — deploy without releasing

```java
// New code only runs for users where the flag is ON
if (featureFlags.isEnabled("new-pricing-v2", userId)) {
    return newPricer.calculate(order);   // new code path
} else {
    return legacyPricer.calculate(order); // old code path (safe fallback)
}
```

**Rollout plan:**
```text
Day 1: Flag ON for your team only (10 people)
Day 2: Flag ON for 1% of users
Day 3: Check metrics — error rate still at 0.02%? ✅
Day 4: Flag ON for 100%
Day 5: Remove old code path
```

---

## Your interview answer

**Open:** "Production behavior is the implicit spec in legacy code. Before touching anything, I capture a risk map of what must never break and record baseline error rate and latency."

**Then:** "I write characterization tests around the exact code I will change — not blanket coverage. For DB-touching code I use Testcontainers to test against real SQL because mocks miss the quirks."

**Then:** "I introduce a seam — extract the dependency — so my new code is small, testable, and reversible. This limits the blast radius."

**End:** "I ship behind a feature flag with canary rollout and watch error rate and latency. If they stay flat, I expand. If they spike, I flip the flag off instantly."

## 🔥 The situation

A batch job processes 1 million records. It stops at 500,000. The UI shows no clear error. Some records were updated, some were not. Re-running might process things twice.

---

## 🧠 Why batch jobs are tricky

A batch job is different from an API request:

| API request | Batch job |
|---|---|
| Takes milliseconds | Takes hours |
| Fails fast and visibly | Can fail silently mid-run |
| Stateless | Must track progress |
| One retry is safe | Retry might double-process |

**The hard problem:** If you re-run after a failure, how do you know what was already done?

---

## Step 1: Find why it stopped — platform or application

**Check if Kubernetes killed the job pod:**
```bash
kubectl describe pod <job-pod-name> -n <namespace>
```

**What you see:**
```text
Last State:     Terminated
  Reason:       OOMKilled
  Exit Code:    137
  Started:      Mon, 08 May 2026 09:00:00
  Finished:     Mon, 08 May 2026 10:30:23
```

**What this means:** Pod ran for 90 minutes then got killed because it used too much memory. Not a code bug — the job needs more memory or processes fewer records per batch.

**Check logs from the crashed container:**
```bash
kubectl logs <job-pod-name> --previous
```

**What you see:**
```text
10:30:20 INFO  Processing record 487523 of 1000000
10:30:21 INFO  Processing record 487524 of 1000000
10:30:22 INFO  Processing record 487525 of 1000000
# ← logs just stop here — pod was killed, no exception
```

**What this means:** Job was at record 487,525 when it died. This is your checkpoint — you know what was done.

---

## Step 2: Design checkpoints — know what was durably saved

**Bad design — one giant transaction:**
```java
// ❌ All 1 million records in one transaction
// If it fails at record 500,000 → all 500,000 changes are rolled back
// Start completely from the beginning
@Transactional
public void processAll() {
    List<Record> all = repo.findAll();  // loads 1M records into memory → OOM
    for (Record r : all) {
        process(r);
    }
    // single commit at the end — any failure = all work lost
}
```

**Good design — process in chunks with checkpoints:**
```java
public void processInChunks() {
    long lastProcessedId = checkpointRepo.getLastId(JOB_NAME).orElse(0L);
    log.info("Resuming from id={}", lastProcessedId);

    while (true) {
        // Load only next 500 records (not all 1M at once)
        List<Record> chunk = repo.findByIdGreaterThan(lastProcessedId, 500);
        if (chunk.isEmpty()) break;

        // Process the chunk
        for (Record r : chunk) { process(r); }

        // Save progress INSIDE same transaction as the data
        lastProcessedId = chunk.get(chunk.size() - 1).getId();
        checkpointRepo.save(JOB_NAME, lastProcessedId);

        log.info("Chunk done: lastId={}, total={}", lastProcessedId, chunk.size());
    }
}
```

**What logs look like (healthy):**
```text
09:00:01 INFO Resuming from id=0
09:00:03 INFO Chunk done: lastId=500, total=500
09:00:05 INFO Chunk done: lastId=1000, total=500
09:00:07 INFO Chunk done: lastId=1500, total=500
...
10:30:20 INFO Chunk done: lastId=487500, total=500
```

**If pod is killed and restarted:**
```text
10:31:00 INFO Resuming from id=487500   ← starts from last checkpoint ✅
10:31:02 INFO Chunk done: lastId=488000, total=500
```

---

## Step 3: Make it idempotent — safe to run twice

**Problem:** Even with checkpoints, a crash between "commit data" and "save checkpoint" can cause re-processing.

```java
// ❌ Plain insert — runs twice = two rows in DB
jdbcTemplate.update("INSERT INTO processed (order_id, result) VALUES (?, ?)",
    orderId, result);

// ✅ Upsert — runs twice = same result, no duplicate
jdbcTemplate.update(
    "INSERT INTO processed (order_id, result) VALUES (?, ?)" +
    " ON CONFLICT (order_id) DO NOTHING",
    orderId, result);
```

**What this means:** Even if a record gets processed twice (because of a crash), the second run does nothing — same outcome either way.

---

## Step 4: Handle poison records — one bad row should not kill a million

```java
for (Record record : chunk) {
    try {
        process(record);
    } catch (DataException ex) {
        // This record is bad — send to Dead Letter Queue and continue
        // Do NOT let one bad record stop 999,999 good ones
        dlqRepo.save(record.getId(), ex.getMessage(), jobRunId);
        log.warn("Skipped bad record id={}, reason={}", record.getId(), ex.getMessage());
    }
}
```

**What logs look like:**
```text
09:05:12 INFO  Chunk done: lastId=5500, total=500
09:05:13 WARN  Skipped bad record id=5341, reason=null value in column "amount"
09:05:13 WARN  Skipped bad record id=5399, reason=invalid date format
09:05:15 INFO  Chunk done: lastId=6000, total=500
# 2 bad records skipped, other 498 processed ✅
```

---

## Your interview answer

**Open:** "Long batch jobs fail silently when the platform kills the pod or a connection times out mid-run — no UI error because the framework has no way to surface it. I start by checking the pod exit reason."

**Then:** "I design the batch in chunks of 500 records with a checkpoint saved after each chunk. If the pod is killed, next run reads the checkpoint and resumes from where it stopped."

**Then:** "Each write is idempotent — using ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING or a natural key upsert — so re-running the same chunk is completely safe."

**End:** "Poison records go to a Dead Letter Queue. One corrupt row should never stop a million good ones. I also log progress per chunk so I can see how far the job has gotten without waiting for it to finish."

## 🔥 The situation
You need to complete a business operation (place an order) that touches multiple services — inventory, payment, shipping. Each has its own database. A traditional database transaction cannot span all three. How do you keep data consistent?

## 🧠 Understand this first

| Approach | How it works | Problem |
|---|---|---|
| Distributed 2PC | One coordinator locks all services, commits together | Slow, requires all services to be available, hard to implement |
| Saga (Choreography) | Each service listens to events and reacts | Hard to trace, event storms |
| Saga (Orchestration) | One orchestrator tells each service what to do, handles failures | Clearer flow, easier to trace — preferred approach |

**Key idea:** Instead of one big transaction, you break it into small local transactions. If step 3 fails, you run compensating transactions to undo steps 1 and 2.

## Step 1: Design the saga steps and compensations

```text
Happy path (forward):
  1. OrderService    → create order (PENDING)
  2. InventoryService → reserve stock
  3. PaymentService   → charge card
  4. OrderService    → mark order CONFIRMED
  5. ShippingService  → create shipment

Failure at step 3 (payment fails):
  → run compensation for step 2: InventoryService.releaseStock()
  → run compensation for step 1: OrderService.cancelOrder()
```

## Step 2: Implement the orchestrator
```java
@Service
public class PlaceOrderSaga {

    public void execute(Order order) {
        try {
            // Step 1: reserve inventory
            inventoryClient.reserve(order.getItems()); // may throw InsufficientStockException

            // Step 2: charge payment
            paymentClient.charge(order.getPayment()); // may throw PaymentFailedException

            // Step 3: confirm
            orderRepo.updateStatus(order.getId(), "CONFIRMED");

        } catch (InsufficientStockException e) {
            // Nothing to compensate yet — inventory already said no
            orderRepo.updateStatus(order.getId(), "CANCELLED");

        } catch (PaymentFailedException e) {
            // Compensate: release the reserved stock
            inventoryClient.releaseReservation(order.getItems());
            orderRepo.updateStatus(order.getId(), "CANCELLED");
        }
    }
}
```

## Step 3: Handle the "what if compensation also fails?" problem

Use the **Outbox pattern** to guarantee compensation messages are sent even if the saga service crashes mid-way.

```java
@Transactional
public void chargeAndSave(Order order) {
    // Save the order state AND the outbox event in ONE local transaction
    orderRepo.save(order);

    outboxRepo.save(new OutboxEvent(
        "inventory-service",
        "RELEASE_RESERVATION",
        order.getId().toString()
    ));
    // If we crash here, both order + outbox event are saved (or neither)
    // A separate poller picks up the outbox event and sends it reliably
}
```

**Outbox table:**
```sql
CREATE TABLE outbox_events (
    id UUID PRIMARY KEY,
    destination VARCHAR(100),  -- which service
    event_type VARCHAR(100),
    payload TEXT,
    published_at TIMESTAMP,    -- null = not sent yet
    created_at TIMESTAMP DEFAULT NOW()
);
```

**Poller that reliably sends events:**
```java
@Scheduled(fixedDelay = 1000)
@Transactional
public void publishPending() {
    List<OutboxEvent> pending = outboxRepo.findByPublishedAtIsNull();
    for (OutboxEvent e : pending) {
        messageBroker.send(e.getDestination(), e.getPayload());
        e.setPublishedAt(Instant.now());
        outboxRepo.save(e);
    }
}
```

**What you see in logs during a payment failure:**
```text
INFO  PlaceOrderSaga - Reserving inventory for order 99
INFO  InventoryService - Reserved 2x Widget for order 99
INFO  PlaceOrderSaga - Charging payment for order 99
ERROR PaymentService - Card declined for order 99
INFO  PlaceOrderSaga - Compensating: releasing inventory for order 99
INFO  InventoryService - Released reservation for order 99
INFO  PlaceOrderSaga - Order 99 marked CANCELLED
```
**What this means (simple):**
- The saga orchestrator ran each step one by one
- Payment failed at step 3
- Compensation automatically released the inventory (step 2 undone)
- Order marked cancelled — no orphaned reservations left in inventory

## Step 4: Make each step idempotent
**Why:** If the network drops after payment but before confirmation, the poller may retry. Payment should not double-charge.

```java
// Payment service — check if already charged
public PaymentResult charge(String orderId, Money amount) {
    if (paymentRepo.existsByOrderId(orderId)) {
        log.info("Already charged for order {}, skipping", orderId);
        return paymentRepo.findByOrderId(orderId); // return existing result
    }
    // ... do actual charge
}
```

## Your interview answer
**Open:** "I'd use the Saga pattern with an orchestrator — one service drives the whole flow step by step."
**Then:** "Each step is a local transaction. If a step fails, the orchestrator calls compensating transactions to undo previous steps. I'd combine this with the Outbox pattern to make sure compensation events are reliably published even if the orchestrator crashes."
**End:** "Each step must be idempotent so retries don't cause double-charges or double-reservations. The outbox guarantees at-least-once delivery. Idempotency handles duplicates."

## 🔥 The situation
Users complain they get randomly logged out — sometimes after 15 minutes, sometimes after hours. No error shown. They just land on the login page again.

## 🧠 Understand this first

| Token type | What it is | Typical lifetime |
|---|---|---|
| Access token | Short-lived — used for API calls | 5–60 minutes |
| Refresh token | Long-lived — used to get new access tokens silently | Hours to days |
| ID token | Contains user info (name, email) | Same as access token |
| Session cookie | Browser-side — stores session state | Configurable |

**The flow when done correctly:**
```text
User logs in
  → gets access token (expires in 15 min) + refresh token (expires in 7 days)

15 min later: access token expires
  → app silently calls /token with refresh token
  → gets a new access token — user never notices

7 days later: refresh token expires
  → can no longer get new tokens
  → user must log in again (expected behavior)
```

**Random logouts = something breaking the silent refresh.**

## Step 1: Check if the refresh token call is even happening
```bash
# In browser DevTools → Network tab → filter by "token"
# Reproduce the logout. Look for a POST to your token endpoint.
```

**What you see (no refresh call — bug):**
```text
(nothing — the app never called /token before logging the user out)
```
**What this means (simple):** The app is not attempting to refresh. The frontend code that handles "access token expired" → "call refresh" is missing or broken.

**What you see (refresh call failed):**
```text
POST /oauth/token  400 Bad Request
{ "error": "invalid_grant", "error_description": "Refresh token expired or revoked" }
```
**What this means (simple):** The refresh token itself expired. This is expected after 7 days but random if it happens after 15 minutes — means refresh token lifetime is misconfigured, OR the refresh token is being rotated and the old one stored in the browser is already invalid.

## Step 2: Check refresh token rotation settings
```bash
# In your OAuth provider dashboard (Okta, Auth0, Keycloak, etc.) look for:
# "Refresh Token Rotation" setting
# If enabled: every time you use a refresh token, you get a NEW one back.
# The old one is immediately invalidated.
```

**What happens with rotation + multiple tabs:**
```text
Tab 1: access token expires → calls /token with refresh_token=ABC → gets new access_token + refresh_token=XYZ
Tab 2: access token expires (same moment) → calls /token with refresh_token=ABC
         → 400 invalid_grant — ABC was already consumed by Tab 1!
         → Tab 2 triggers logout
```
**What this means (simple):** Two browser tabs racing to refresh causes one to win and one to get logged out. The fix is to coordinate refresh across tabs.

**Fix — use a mutex/lock for refresh:**
```javascript
// Shared lock across tabs using BroadcastChannel or localStorage
let isRefreshing = false;
let refreshSubscribers = [];

async function refreshToken() {
  if (isRefreshing) {
    // Someone else is already refreshing — wait for their result
    return new Promise((resolve) => refreshSubscribers.push(resolve));
  }
  isRefreshing = true;
  try {
    const response = await fetch('/oauth/token', {
      method: 'POST',
      body: new URLSearchParams({
        grant_type: 'refresh_token',
        refresh_token: getStoredRefreshToken(),
      }),
    });
    const tokens = await response.json();
    storeTokens(tokens);
    refreshSubscribers.forEach(cb => cb(tokens.access_token));
    refreshSubscribers = [];
    return tokens.access_token;
  } finally {
    isRefreshing = false;
  }
}
```

## Step 3: Check clock skew (very common cause)
**Why:** Access tokens have an `exp` (expiry) field. Your server checks `exp` against its own clock. If server clock is 5 minutes ahead of the issuer, it rejects tokens that are still valid.

```bash
# Check server clock vs real time
date -u
curl -s http://worldtimeapi.org/api/ip | grep utc_datetime
```

**What you see (skew problem):**
```text
Server: 10:32:00 UTC
Real:   10:27:00 UTC
Difference: 5 minutes — tokens expire 5 min early on this server
```

**Fix — add a clock skew leeway in your JWT validation:**
```java
// With Nimbus JOSE (Spring Security uses this internally)
JWTClaimsSet claims = signedJWT.getJWTClaimsSet();
Date expiry = claims.getExpirationTime();
long leewaySeconds = 60; // allow 60 seconds of clock drift
if (expiry.getTime() + leewaySeconds * 1000 < System.currentTimeMillis()) {
    throw new BadJOSEException("Token expired");
}

// With Spring Security OAuth2:
// application.yml
spring:
  security:
    oauth2:
      resourceserver:
        jwt:
          jws-algorithms: RS256
# Spring auto-handles leeway via NimbusJwtDecoder — set it explicitly:
@Bean
NimbusJwtDecoder jwtDecoder() {
    NimbusJwtDecoder decoder = NimbusJwtDecoder.withJwkSetUri(jwkSetUri).build();
    decoder.setClockSkew(Duration.ofSeconds(60)); // accept tokens 60s past expiry
    return decoder;
}
```

## Step 4: Check where refresh tokens are stored
```javascript
// BAD: localStorage — survives page close, but accessible by any JS (XSS risk)
localStorage.setItem('refresh_token', token);

// BAD: sessionStorage — lost when tab closes → logout on tab close
sessionStorage.setItem('refresh_token', token);

// GOOD: HttpOnly cookie — JS cannot read it, sent automatically, survives tab close
// Server sets it:
// Set-Cookie: refresh_token=XYZ; HttpOnly; Secure; SameSite=Strict; Path=/oauth/token
```
**What this means (simple):** If refresh token is in sessionStorage, closing a tab = logout. If in localStorage, an XSS attack can steal it. HttpOnly cookies are safest — the browser sends them automatically, JS can never read them.

## Your interview answer
**Open:** "I'd check three things: whether the frontend is even attempting a token refresh, whether refresh token rotation is causing multi-tab race conditions, and whether there's clock skew between the token issuer and the resource server."
**Then:** "For multi-tab races, I'd add a refresh lock so only one tab refreshes at a time. For clock skew, I'd add a 60-second leeway to JWT validation. For storage, I'd move refresh tokens to HttpOnly cookies."
**End:** "Random logouts almost always trace back to one of these three root causes — the fix is identifying which one using browser network logs and server-side JWT validation logs."

## 🔥 The situation
Your OAuth provider (Okta, Auth0, Keycloak, etc.) is down. Users cannot log in. But they are already logged in — should they be able to keep using the app? How do you design for auth provider outages?

## 🧠 Understand this first

| Scenario | What happens without prep | What happens with prep |
|---|---|---|
| Provider down, user already logged in | JWT validation calls provider → fails → user kicked out | Token validated locally from cached JWK → user stays logged in |
| Provider down, user tries to log in | Login page hangs → user can't access | Show maintenance message immediately |
| Provider down, service-to-service token expired | Cannot fetch new token → all M2M calls fail | Cached token still valid for remaining 5 min window |
| Provider returns JWK keys slowly | Every request waits for slow JWK fetch → latency spike | JWK keys cached locally for hours |
| Provider back up | Everything works again | Same |

## Step 1: Cache JWK keys locally (most important fix)
**Why:** By default, Spring Security fetches the JWK Set (public keys) from the provider on each request or at intervals. If provider is down → can't fetch keys → can't validate tokens → 401 for all users.

```java
@Bean
NimbusJwtDecoder jwtDecoder() {
    // This caches the JWK Set in memory
    // Spring Security does this by default with a 5-minute refresh interval
    return NimbusJwtDecoder
        .withJwkSetUri("https://auth.example.com/.well-known/jwks.json")
        .cache(Duration.ofHours(1))   // ← cache keys for 1 hour
        .build();
}
```

**What this means (simple):** JWT validation only needs the public key. Public keys almost never change (key rotation happens rarely). Caching them for 1 hour means if the provider goes down for 30 minutes, your existing JWTs are still validated successfully from the cache.

**What you see in logs during outage (with cache — good):**
```text
DEBUG NimbusJwtDecoder - Using cached JWK set (expires in 47 minutes)
DEBUG JwtAuthenticationProvider - Authenticated user-123 from cached keys
// Users stay logged in — no provider contact needed
```

**What you see in logs during outage (without cache — bad):**
```text
ERROR NimbusJwtDecoder - Failed to fetch JWK Set from https://auth.example.com/.well-known/jwks.json
ERROR JwtAuthenticationProvider - Unable to validate token — returning 401
// All users kicked out
```

## Step 2: Don't call the provider's introspection endpoint on every request
```java
// BAD: calling introspection on every request (provider down = every request fails)
@Bean
OpaqueTokenIntrospector introspector() {
    return new NimbusOpaqueTokenIntrospector(
        "https://auth.example.com/introspect",  // remote call every time
        "client-id",
        "client-secret"
    );
}

// GOOD: use JWTs — validate locally with cached public key
// No remote call per request — just local signature verification
@Bean
SecurityFilterChain securityFilterChain(HttpSecurity http) throws Exception {
    http.oauth2ResourceServer(oauth2 -> oauth2.jwt(Customizer.withDefaults()));
    return http.build();
}
```
**What this means (simple):** Opaque tokens are random strings — the server must call the provider to ask "is this token valid?" every time. JWTs contain their own claims and can be verified locally with the cached public key. JWTs are resilient to provider outages; opaque tokens are not.

## Step 3: Handle login failures gracefully
```java
// In your login controller or security config — catch provider connection errors
@GetMapping("/login/callback")
public ResponseEntity<?> handleCallback(@RequestParam String code, HttpServletResponse resp) {
    try {
        TokenResponse tokens = oauthClient.exchangeCode(code);
        // ... set session
        return ResponseEntity.status(302).header("Location", "/dashboard").build();

    } catch (HttpClientErrorException | ResourceAccessException e) {
        // Provider is down or returning errors
        log.error("OAuth provider unavailable during login: {}", e.getMessage());
        return ResponseEntity.status(302)
            .header("Location", "/error?reason=auth_unavailable")
            .build();
    }
}
```

**What the user sees (good):**
```text
We're having trouble reaching our login provider. Please try again in a few minutes.
[Status page link]
```

**What the user sees (bad — no handling):**
```text
(browser spinner for 30 seconds, then generic "something went wrong" error)
```

## Step 4: Circuit breaker for OAuth provider calls
```java
// Wrap the token endpoint call in a circuit breaker
@CircuitBreaker(name = "authProvider", fallbackMethod = "loginFallback")
public TokenResponse fetchToken(String code) {
    return oauthClient.exchangeCode(code);
}

public TokenResponse loginFallback(String code, Exception e) {
    log.warn("Auth provider circuit open — login unavailable");
    throw new AuthProviderUnavailableException("Login temporarily unavailable");
}
```

```yaml
resilience4j:
  circuitbreaker:
    instances:
      authProvider:
        slidingWindowSize: 5
        failureRateThreshold: 60     # open if 60% of 5 calls fail
        waitDurationInOpenState: 30s # wait 30s before trying again
```

**What you see in logs during outage:**
```text
INFO  CircuitBreaker - authProvider: CLOSED → OPEN (failure rate 80%)
