## The problem — synchronous chain

```java
// ❌ CURRENT — synchronous, everything in one thread
@PostMapping("/register")
@Transactional
public User register(@RequestBody RegisterRequest request) {
    User user = userRepo.save(new User(request));   // 50ms
    emailService.sendWelcomeEmail(user);             // 800ms — external SMTP call
    storageService.provisionBucket(user.getId());   // 1200ms — S3/MinIO API call
    crmService.createContact(user);                  // 900ms — external CRM API call
    return user;
    // Total: ~3000ms per registration — user waits 3 seconds
}
```

The user only needs the account to be CREATED to start using the app. Email, storage, and CRM can happen asynchronously. They are NOT part of the core transaction.

---

## The fix — async with Kafka

### Step 1: Registration endpoint — thin and fast

```java
// ✅ NEW — save user, emit event, return in 60ms
@PostMapping("/register")
@Transactional
public ResponseEntity<UserAck> register(@RequestBody RegisterRequest request) {
    // Validate + save — this IS the core operation
    if (userRepo.existsByEmail(request.getEmail())) {
        throw new EmailAlreadyExistsException(request.getEmail());
    }
    User user = userRepo.save(User.builder()
        .email(request.getEmail())
        .passwordHash(passwordEncoder.encode(request.getPassword()))
        .status(UserStatus.ACTIVE)
        .build());

    // Publish ONE event — all downstream services react independently
    kafka.send("user.registered", user.getId().toString(),
        new UserRegisteredEvent(
            user.getId(),
            user.getEmail(),
            user.getFullName(),
            Instant.now()
        ));

    log.info("User {} registered, event published", user.getId());

    // Return 201 immediately — don't wait for email/storage/CRM
    return ResponseEntity
        .status(HttpStatus.CREATED)
        .body(new UserAck(user.getId(), user.getEmail(), "Account created"));
    // Response time: ~60ms instead of ~3000ms
}
```

### Step 2: Define the event contract

```java
// Event payload — clear contract between producer and consumers
@Value
@Builder
@JsonSerialize
public class UserRegisteredEvent {
    UUID userId;
    String email;
    String fullName;
    Instant registeredAt;
    // Don't put password or sensitive data in events
}
```

### Step 3: Independent consumers per domain

```java
// Email service consumer — own consumer group
@Component
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class WelcomeEmailConsumer {

    private final EmailService emailService;

    @KafkaListener(
        topics = "user.registered",
        groupId = "email-service",   // different group ID per service
        concurrency = "3"            // 3 concurrent threads
    )
    public void sendWelcomeEmail(UserRegisteredEvent event) {
        emailService.sendWelcome(event.getEmail(), event.getFullName());
        log.info("Welcome email sent to {}", event.getEmail());
    }
}

// Storage service consumer — completely independent
@Component
public class StorageProvisionConsumer {

    @KafkaListener(topics = "user.registered", groupId = "storage-service")
    public void provisionBucket(UserRegisteredEvent event) {
        storageService.createUserBucket(event.getUserId().toString());
        log.info("Storage bucket created for user {}", event.getUserId());
    }
}

// CRM consumer — completely independent
@Component
public class CrmSyncConsumer {

    @KafkaListener(topics = "user.registered", groupId = "crm-service")
    public void syncToCrm(UserRegisteredEvent event) {
        crmClient.createContact(event.getEmail(), event.getFullName());
        log.info("CRM contact created for user {}", event.getUserId());
    }
}
```

**Why separate `groupId` per consumer?** Each consumer group gets ALL events independently. Three different group IDs → every registration event is delivered to ALL three consumers separately.

---

## Expected log output after the change

**API response (immediate):**
```text
HTTP/1.1 201 Created
Content-Type: application/json

{"userId": "abc-123", "email": "user@example.com", "message": "Account created"}

Response time: 58ms (down from 3000ms)
```

**Consumer logs (async, after response already sent):**
```text
10:30:01.058 INFO  UserService          - User abc-123 registered, event published
10:30:01.112 INFO  WelcomeEmailConsumer - Welcome email sent to user@example.com
10:30:01.145 INFO  StorageConsumer      - Storage bucket created for user abc-123
10:30:01.201 INFO  CrmSyncConsumer      - CRM contact created for user abc-123
```

Notice: the API returned at 58ms, the downstream processing happened from 112ms onward — after the user already got their response.

---

## Add retry + DLQ for consumer failures

```java
@Configuration
public class KafkaConfig {

    @Bean
    public DefaultErrorHandler errorHandler(
            KafkaTemplate<String, Object> template) {

        DeadLetterPublishingRecoverer recoverer =
            new DeadLetterPublishingRecoverer(template,
                (record, ex) -> new TopicPartition(
                    record.topic() + ".DLT", 0));

        // Retry 3 times with 1s, 2s, 4s backoff
        ExponentialBackOff backoff = new ExponentialBackOff(1000L, 2.0);
        backoff.setMaxAttempts(3);

        return new DefaultErrorHandler(recoverer, backoff);
    }
}
```

If `emailService.sendWelcome()` fails (SMTP down), the event is retried 3 times with exponential backoff, then moved to `user.registered.DLT` (Dead Letter Topic) for manual inspection.

---

## Your interview answer

> "The root cause was coupling: registration tied to 3 external API calls in one synchronous thread. I refactored to an event-driven model: register the user in the DB, publish a user.registered event to Kafka, return 201 immediately. Each downstream concern — email, storage, CRM — has its own consumer group and processes independently. If CRM is down, it doesn't affect email or the user experience. Each consumer retries with exponential backoff and falls back to a DLT. Response time went from 3 seconds to 60ms."

followUps.answer:
When Kafka is down, your producer `kafka.send()` call will fail. For the registration endpoint, this means the user account IS saved to DB but the event is NOT published → email never sent, CRM not notified.

**Approach 1 — Outbox pattern (most reliable)**:
Instead of publishing to Kafka directly, write the event to an outbox table in the same DB transaction. A relay poller publishes to Kafka when it recovers. The user sees 201, the event is durably stored.

**Approach 2 — Kafka retry with circuit breaker:**
```java
@CircuitBreaker(name = "kafka", fallbackMethod = "kafkaFallback")
public void publishEvent(UserRegisteredEvent event) {
    kafka.send("user.registered", event.getUserId().toString(), event).get(5, SECONDS);
}

public void kafkaFallback(UserRegisteredEvent event, Throwable ex) {
    // Save to retry table for later
    retryQueue.save(PendingEvent.of("user.registered", event));
    log.warn("Kafka unavailable. Event saved to retry queue: {}", event.getUserId());
}

@Scheduled(fixedDelay = 60000)
public void retryPendingEvents() {
    List<PendingEvent> pending = retryQueue.findAll();
    for (PendingEvent e : pending) {
        try {
            kafka.send(e.getTopic(), e.getPayload()).get();
            retryQueue.delete(e);
        } catch (Exception ex) {
            log.warn("Retry failed for event {}", e.getId());
        }
    }
}
```

**Approach 3 — Make registration idempotent so you can replay:**
Ensure all consumers are idempotent — if a user.registered event is replayed, they don't send a duplicate welcome email.

