## The situation

50,000 DB queries/min for 200 products = each product is fetched ~250 times per minute. These products change at most once per day. This is the perfect candidate for caching.

Last time it went wrong because: no TTL (data never expired), no invalidation on update, and no stampede protection.

---

## Pattern 1: Cache-Aside (most common, most control)

```java
@Service
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class ProductService {

    private final ProductRepository productRepo;
    private final RedisTemplate<String, Product> redis;
    private final Random random = new Random();

    private static final int BASE_TTL_SECONDS = 3600; // 1 hour
    private static final int TTL_JITTER_SECONDS = 300; // ±5 min jitter

    public Product getProduct(Long productId) {
        String key = cacheKey(productId);

        // 1. Try cache
        Product cached = redis.opsForValue().get(key);
        if (cached != null) {
            return cached;  // cache HIT — DB not touched
        }

        // 2. Cache MISS — go to DB
        Product product = productRepo.findById(productId)
            .orElseThrow(() -> new ProductNotFoundException(productId));

        // 3. Store in cache with TTL + jitter
        // Jitter prevents all products from expiring at the same time (stampede)
        int ttl = BASE_TTL_SECONDS + random.nextInt(TTL_JITTER_SECONDS);
        redis.opsForValue().set(key, product, ttl, TimeUnit.SECONDS);

        log.debug("Cache MISS for product:{} → fetched from DB, cached for {}s", productId, ttl);
        return product;
    }

    // CRITICAL: invalidate cache on every update
    @Transactional
    public Product updateProduct(Long productId, ProductUpdateRequest request) {
        Product product = productRepo.findById(productId)
            .orElseThrow(() -> new ProductNotFoundException(productId));

        product.setPrice(request.getPrice());
        product.setStock(request.getStock());
        productRepo.save(product);

        // Evict from cache AFTER successful DB save
        redis.delete(cacheKey(productId));
        log.info("Product {} updated in DB and evicted from cache", productId);

        return product;
    }

    private String cacheKey(Long productId) {
        return "product:" + productId;
    }
}
```

**Why this fixes your previous problem**: Every `updateProduct()` call deletes the Redis key. Next read is a cache miss → fetches fresh data from DB → caches it. Users never see stale prices for more than the time between the update and the next cache miss (which is immediate after update).

---

## Pattern 2: Spring Cache with @Cacheable (simpler)

```yaml
spring:
  cache:
    type: redis
  data:
    redis:
      time-to-live: 3600000  # 1 hour in ms
```

```java
@Service
@CacheConfig(cacheNames = "products")
public class ProductService {

    @Cacheable(key = "#productId")
    public Product getProduct(Long productId) {
        return productRepo.findById(productId)
            .orElseThrow(() -> new ProductNotFoundException(productId));
        // Spring automatically caches the return value
    }

    @CacheEvict(key = "#productId")  // removes from cache on update
    public Product updateProduct(Long productId, ProductUpdateRequest request) {
        // DB update logic
        return productRepo.save(updated);
    }

    @CacheEvict(allEntries = true)  // nuclear option — clear all product cache
    @Scheduled(cron = "0 0 3 * * *")  // every night at 3 AM
    public void evictAllProductCache() {
        log.info("Full product cache eviction");
    }
}
```

---

## Cache stampede prevention with mutex lock

The scenario: Product with ID 101 expires at exactly 10:35 AM. At that moment, 500 concurrent requests all miss the cache and simultaneously query the DB for product 101.

```java
public Product getProduct(Long productId) {
    String key = cacheKey(productId);
    String lockKey = "lock:" + key;

    Product cached = redis.opsForValue().get(key);
    if (cached != null) return cached;

    // Distributed mutex — only ONE thread rebuilds the cache
    Boolean locked = redis.opsForValue().setIfAbsent(lockKey, "1", 10, TimeUnit.SECONDS);

    if (Boolean.TRUE.equals(locked)) {
        try {
            // Re-check cache (another thread may have populated it)
            cached = redis.opsForValue().get(key);
            if (cached != null) return cached;

            // We have the lock — fetch from DB and populate cache
            Product product = productRepo.findById(productId).orElseThrow();
            redis.opsForValue().set(key, product,
                BASE_TTL_SECONDS + random.nextInt(TTL_JITTER_SECONDS), TimeUnit.SECONDS);
            return product;
        } finally {
            redis.delete(lockKey);
        }
    } else {
        // Another thread is rebuilding — wait briefly and retry from cache
        try { Thread.sleep(50); } catch (InterruptedException e) { Thread.currentThread().interrupt(); }
        cached = redis.opsForValue().get(key);
        return cached != null ? cached : productRepo.findById(productId).orElseThrow();
    }
}
```

---

## What you see in Redis after implementation

```bash
# Check what's in Redis
redis-cli KEYS 'product:*'
# Output: product:101  product:102  product:103  ...

# Check TTL of a key
redis-cli TTL product:101
# Output: 3742  (seconds until expiry — 1 hour + jitter)

# Monitor cache hit rate via Redis INFO
redis-cli INFO stats | grep keyspace
# Output:
# keyspace_hits: 2847330     ← reads served from cache
# keyspace_misses: 12450     ← cache misses, went to DB
# Hit rate: 2847330/(2847330+12450) = 99.6%
```

---

## Your interview answer

> "I used the cache-aside pattern with Redis. On every read, check Redis first — if miss, fetch from DB and cache the result with TTL plus random jitter. The jitter is critical: without it, all 200 product keys cached at the same time all expire at the same time, causing 500 simultaneous DB queries — a stampede. On every update, explicitly evict the cache key. This means the next read gets fresh data. We went from 50,000 DB queries/min to under 500 (1% cache miss rate), and CPU dropped from 85% to 12%."

---

## Cache hierarchy for high-traffic services

```text
Request → L1 (Caffeine in-memory, 1ms) → L2 (Redis, 5ms) → DB (50ms)

// Two-level cache with Caffeine + Redis
@Bean
public CacheManager cacheManager(RedisConnectionFactory redis) {
    return new CompositeCacheManager(
        new CaffeineCacheManager(),  // L1: local, very fast, small
        new RedisCacheManager.create(redis)  // L2: distributed, shared
    );
}
```

L1 Caffeine: 100ms TTL, max 500 entries per JVM. Absorbs hot traffic without Redis round-trips. L2 Redis: 1 hour TTL, shared across all instances.

followUps.answer:
**Cache-aside** (lazy loading): App checks cache, misses, reads DB, then writes to cache.
- Cache is populated on demand
- First read after startup: cache miss → DB
- If Redis goes down: fall through to DB (resilient)

**Write-through**: Every DB write ALSO writes to cache synchronously. Cache always has the latest value.

```java
// Write-through pattern
@Transactional
public Product updateProduct(Long productId, ProductUpdateRequest request) {
    Product product = productRepo.findById(productId).orElseThrow();
    product.setPrice(request.getPrice());
    productRepo.save(product);

    // Write to cache immediately — not evict, but update
    redis.opsForValue().set("product:" + productId, product, 1, TimeUnit.HOURS);
    return product;
}
```

**When to use write-through**:
- Read-heavy workloads where you want ZERO cold start (cache always pre-populated)
- User sessions — when user logs in, session is immediately in Redis
- Config/settings — infrequent writes, very frequent reads

**When to use cache-aside**:
- When you don't want to cache everything, just frequently-accessed items
- When cache miss and falling back to DB is acceptable
- Simpler to implement correctly

**Write-behind** (async write-through): Write to cache, return success to client, write to DB asynchronously. Fastest but risk of data loss if cache crashes.

If you use **Redis** as your cache: all instances share the same Redis, so an eviction from instance A is immediately visible to instances B and C. This is the main reason to use Redis over in-memory caching in distributed environments.

```text
Instance A (pod-1) → evict product:101 → Redis
Instance B (pod-2) → reads product:101 → cache MISS → fetches from DB
Instance C (pod-3) → reads product:101 → cache MISS → fetches from DB

→ Both B and C get fresh data after A's eviction ✓
```

**Problem with local Caffeine cache in multiple instances:**
```text
Instance A → evict product:101 (its local Caffeine cache)
Instance B → has product:101 in ITS Caffeine cache (stale!)
User goes to Instance B → sees old price
```

**Fix: Cache invalidation broadcast with Spring Application Events or Redis Pub/Sub:**
```java
@Service
public class ProductService {

    @Transactional
    public Product updateProduct(Long id, ProductUpdateRequest req) {
        Product saved = productRepo.save(updated);

        // Broadcast invalidation to ALL instances
        redis.convertAndSend("cache.invalidation", "product:" + id);
        return saved;
    }
}

@Component
public class CacheInvalidationListener {

    private final Cache<String, Product> localCache; // Caffeine

    @EventListener
    public void onInvalidation(String key) {
        localCache.invalidate(key); // Every instance evicts from its local cache
        log.info("Local cache evicted key: {}", key);
    }
}
```

General rule: **Use Redis for shared state, Caffeine as read-only warm local cache with short TTL (30-60s)**.

**1. No cache invalidation on update** (the stale data problem):
```java
// ❌ updates DB but forgets cache
public void updateProduct(Long id, ...) { productRepo.save(p); }
// ✅ always evict
public void updateProduct(Long id, ...) { productRepo.save(p); redis.delete("product:"+id); }
```

**2. Infinite TTL (or no TTL)**:
```java
// ❌ never expires
redis.opsForValue().set(key, value);
// ✅ always set TTL
redis.opsForValue().set(key, value, 3600, TimeUnit.SECONDS);
```

**3. Caching too broadly** (caching user-specific or session-specific data by wrong key):
```java
// ❌ wrong key — same product cached once, returned to all users
redis.opsForValue().set("product", product);  // missing the ID!
// ✅
redis.opsForValue().set("product:" + productId, product, ...);
```

**4. Cache stampede** — fixed with TTL jitter (covered above).

**5. Not monitoring cache hit rate**:
```bash
redis-cli INFO stats | grep -E 'keyspace_hits|keyspace_misses'
```
If hit rate < 80%, your caching strategy is wrong — you're not caching the right things. Target > 95% for high-read workloads.

scenarios.answer:
## The situation

```text
Partner script: 8000 req/min = ~133 req/sec
Your API capacity: ~1000 req/min before DB pool exhausts
Internal users: getting 503 because partner took all connections

Problem:
  No rate limiting → one client can monopolize the entire API
  Need: per-client limits so one client can't starve others
```

---

## Understand the algorithms

```text
Fixed Window: count requests in 1-minute buckets
  12:00-12:01 → 100 requests ✓
  12:01-12:02 → 100 requests ✓
  Problem: burst of 200 requests from 12:00:59 to 12:01:01
  (100 in window 1, 100 in window 2 — all pass)

Sliding Window: count requests in the LAST 60 seconds
  At any point: if last 60s had 100 requests → block next
  No burst exploitation, but more complex

Token Bucket: tokens accumulate at rate R, max B tokens
  100 tokens/min refill rate, max bucket 100
  Client can burst up to 100, then limited to 100/min
  Best for APIs with natural burst behavior
```

---

## Implementation 1 — Redis sliding window (per API key)

```java
@Component
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class RateLimiterService {

    private final RedisTemplate<String, String> redis;
    private final RateLimiterConfig config;

    /**
     * Sliding window rate limiter using Redis sorted set.
     * Returns true if request is allowed, false if rate limited.
     */
    public boolean isAllowed(String apiKey) {
        long now = System.currentTimeMillis();
        long windowStart = now - config.getWindowMs(); // e.g., last 60000ms = 1 min
        String key = "ratelimit:" + apiKey;

        List<Object> results = redis.executePipelined((RedisCallback<Object>) connection -> {
            StringRedisConnection conn = (StringRedisConnection) connection;

            // Remove requests older than the window
            conn.zRemRangeByScore(key, 0, windowStart);

            // Count requests in current window
            conn.zCard(key);

            // Add this request with timestamp as score
            conn.zAdd(key, now, now + ":" + UUID.randomUUID());

            // Set key expiry to window size + buffer
            conn.expire(key, config.getWindowMs() / 1000 + 10);

            return null;
        });

        Long requestCount = (Long) results.get(1); // count BEFORE adding this request
        boolean allowed = requestCount < config.getMaxRequests();

        if (!allowed) {
            log.warn("Rate limit exceeded for API key: {} (count: {})", apiKey, requestCount);
        }
        return allowed;
    }

    public long getRemainingRequests(String apiKey) {
        long windowStart = System.currentTimeMillis() - config.getWindowMs();
        redis.opsForZSet().removeRangeByScore("ratelimit:" + apiKey, 0, windowStart);
        Long count = redis.opsForZSet().zCard("ratelimit:" + apiKey);
        return Math.max(0, config.getMaxRequests() - (count != null ? count : 0));
    }
}
```

### Wire it as a filter

```java
@Component
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class RateLimitFilter extends OncePerRequestFilter {

    private final RateLimiterService rateLimiter;
    private final RateLimiterConfig config;

    @Override
    protected void doFilterInternal(HttpServletRequest request,
            HttpServletResponse response, FilterChain chain)
            throws ServletException, IOException {

        String apiKey = request.getHeader("X-API-Key");
        if (apiKey == null) {
            response.setStatus(HttpStatus.UNAUTHORIZED.value());
            response.getWriter().write("{\"error\": \"Missing X-API-Key header\"}");
            return;
        }

        if (!rateLimiter.isAllowed(apiKey)) {
            long remaining = rateLimiter.getRemainingRequests(apiKey);

            response.setStatus(HttpStatus.TOO_MANY_REQUESTS.value()); // 429
            response.setHeader("X-RateLimit-Limit",
                String.valueOf(config.getMaxRequests()));
            response.setHeader("X-RateLimit-Remaining", String.valueOf(remaining));
            response.setHeader("Retry-After",
                String.valueOf(config.getWindowMs() / 1000)); // seconds to wait
            response.setContentType("application/json");
            response.getWriter().write(
                "{\"error\": \"Too many requests\", \"retryAfterSeconds\": "
                + config.getWindowMs() / 1000 + "}");
            return;
        }

        // Add rate limit headers to successful responses too
        response.setHeader("X-RateLimit-Limit",
            String.valueOf(config.getMaxRequests()));
        response.setHeader("X-RateLimit-Remaining",
            String.valueOf(rateLimiter.getRemainingRequests(apiKey)));

        chain.doFilter(request, response);
    }
}
```

