## Your interview answer

> "I implemented a per-API-key sliding window rate limiter using Redis sorted sets. Each API key gets its own sorted set where the score is the request timestamp. On each request, I remove entries older than 60 seconds, count the remaining entries, and check against the per-tier limit. If exceeded, return 429 with a Retry-After header. This gives per-client isolation — the partner script hitting its limit doesn't affect internal users. The sorted set approach uses O(log N) operations and handles burst correctly since it's time-based, not bucket-reset-based."

