## Step 3 — Mass invalidation on password change

```java
@Service
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class UserService {

    private final UserRepository userRepo;
    private final PasswordEncoder passwordEncoder;

    @Transactional
    public void changePassword(Long userId, ChangePasswordRequest request) {
        User user = userRepo.findById(userId).orElseThrow();

        if (!passwordEncoder.matches(request.getCurrentPassword(), user.getPasswordHash())) {
            throw new InvalidPasswordException("Current password is incorrect");
        }

        user.setPasswordHash(passwordEncoder.encode(request.getNewPassword()));

        // Increment version — ALL existing tokens (even valid ones) are now invalid
        user.setTokenVersion(user.getTokenVersion() + 1);
        userRepo.save(user);

        log.info("Password changed for user {} — token version bumped to {}",
            userId, user.getTokenVersion());
        // All existing JWTs have the old version — they'll be rejected at validation
    }
}
```

**Effect**: User changes password → `tokenVersion` goes from 5 to 6. Every active token contains `version: 5`. On next API call, the filter checks `token.version != user.tokenVersion` → 401 Unauthorized → user must log in again.

