## Your interview answer

> "SQL LIKE queries with leading wildcards can't use indexes — they do a full table scan on 5M rows. I migrated search to Elasticsearch which uses an inverted index: O(1) lookup regardless of dataset size. I set up a custom analyzer with synonyms (running = jogging, shoes = sneakers) and stemming so 'run shoe' matches 'Running Shoes'. The ES index is populated via a Kafka consumer that syncs every product change from PostgreSQL. Search went from 8-10 seconds to under 10ms for 5M products, and match quality improved significantly."

followUps.answer:
Elasticsearch should be a search enhancement, not a critical dependency. If it's down, fallback to PostgreSQL full-text search.

**Resilient search service with circuit breaker:**
```java
@Service
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class SearchService {

    private final ProductSearchService esSearch;
    private final ProductRepository postgresSearch;

    @CircuitBreaker(name = "elasticsearch", fallbackMethod = "fallbackSearch")
    @TimeLimiter(name = "elasticsearch")
    public CompletableFuture<SearchResult> search(ProductSearchRequest request) {
        return CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> {
            SearchHits<ProductDocument> hits = esSearch.search(request);
            return SearchResult.from(hits);
        });
    }

    // Fallback to PostgreSQL full-text search
    public CompletableFuture<SearchResult> fallbackSearch(
            ProductSearchRequest request, Throwable ex) {
        log.warn("Elasticsearch unavailable, falling back to PostgreSQL: {}",
            ex.getMessage());
        // PostgreSQL full-text search is slower but works
        List<Product> results = postgresSearch.findByNameContainingIgnoreCase(
            request.getKeyword(), request.getPageable());
        return CompletableFuture.completedFuture(SearchResult.fromProducts(results));
    }
}
```

**Handling sync lag (ES slightly behind PostgreSQL):**
For freshly created products, use `refresh=wait_for` to ensure ES is in sync before returning:
```java
IndexQuery query = new IndexQueryBuilder()
    .withObject(productDocument)
    .build();
esOps.index(query, IndexCoordinates.of("products"));
esOps.indexOps(ProductDocument.class).refresh(); // force refresh
```

For most use cases, 1-second eventual consistency is acceptable.

**Approach 1: Search-as-you-type field type (simplest):**

```java
@Document(indexName = "products")
public class ProductDocument {
    @Field(type = FieldType.Search_As_You_Type)
    private String name;  // Elasticsearch auto-creates shingles (2-gram, 3-gram)
}
```

```java
public List<String> autocomplete(String prefix) {
    NativeQuery query = NativeQuery.builder()
        .withQuery(QueryBuilders.multiMatch(mm -> mm
            .query(prefix)
            .type(TextQueryType.BoolPrefix)
            .fields("name", "name._2gram", "name._3gram")
        ))
        .withPageable(PageRequest.of(0, 10))
        .build();

    SearchHits<ProductDocument> hits = esOps.search(query, ProductDocument.class);
    return hits.stream()
        .map(h -> h.getContent().getName())
        .distinct()
        .collect(Collectors.toList());
}
```

**Approach 2: Completion suggester (faster, good for brand/category suggestions):**

```java
@Field(type = FieldType.Completion)
private Completion nameSuggestion;  // Elasticsearch's in-memory completion index
```

```bash
# Query completion suggester
curl 'http://es:9200/products/_search' -d '{
  "suggest": {
    "product-suggest": {
      "prefix": "run",
      "completion": {
        "field": "nameSuggestion",
        "size": 5,
        "fuzzy": {"fuzziness": 1}
      }
    }
  }
}'

# Response: ["Running Shoes", "Running Shorts", "Running Watch", ...]
# Response time: ~2ms (in-memory FST data structure)
```

**When to use**:
- Search-as-you-type: keyword autocomplete in search bar
- Completion suggester: brand/category autocomplete where you control the suggestions

