## Alternative: Redis-based lock (for non-DB environments)

```xml
<dependency>
  <groupId>net.javacrumbs.shedlock</groupId>
  <artifactId>shedlock-provider-redis-spring</artifactId>
  <version>5.10.0</version>
</dependency>
```

```java
@Bean
public LockProvider lockProvider(RedisConnectionFactory redisConnectionFactory) {
    return new RedisLockProvider(redisConnectionFactory, "production");
    // Stores locks as Redis keys with TTL = lockAtMostFor
}
```

```bash
# What ShedLock does in Redis:
redis-cli GET shedlock:monthly-billing-job
# Output: "pod-1:2024-01-01T00:30:00"
# → Pod-1 holds the lock until 00:30 AM

# After job completes:
redis-cli GET shedlock:monthly-billing-job
# Output: nil  ← released
```

---

## lockAtMostFor vs lockAtLeastFor — why both matter

```text
lockAtMostFor = "30m":
  If Pod-1 JVM crashes mid-job, the lock auto-releases after 30 minutes.
  Without this: lock is held forever → no instance can run the job next month.

lockAtLeastFor = "5m":
  Even if the job finishes in 30 seconds, hold the lock for 5 minutes.
  Why? If clock skew or network issue causes a second instance to start slightly
  late, it won't pick up the lock and re-run a job that just finished.
```

---

## Your interview answer

> "The root issue is that @Scheduled runs in every JVM independently — there's no awareness of other instances. I added ShedLock which uses a database lock table to ensure only one instance acquires the lock and runs the job. The lock row has a name (unique per job), locked_by (instance hostname), and lock_until (auto-release for crash safety). The other instances try to INSERT the same row, fail on the primary key constraint, and skip execution. I set lockAtMostFor=30min so the lock auto-releases if the JVM crashes, and lockAtLeastFor=5min to prevent rapid re-execution."

---

## Job idempotency as safety net

Even with ShedLock, make jobs idempotent in case of duplicate runs:

```java
public void generateAndSendInvoice(Customer customer) {
    // Check if invoice already sent this month
    YearMonth currentMonth = YearMonth.now();
    if (invoiceRepo.existsByCustomerIdAndMonth(customer.getId(), currentMonth)) {
        log.info("Invoice already sent for customer {} month {}",
            customer.getId(), currentMonth);
        return;  // Skip — idempotent
    }
    // ... create and send invoice
}
```

followUps.answer:
By default, `@Scheduled` fires again even if the previous run is still going. This can cause:
1. Two instances of the same job running simultaneously (race condition)
2. Resource exhaustion (DB connections, memory)

**Fix 1 — ShedLock with lockAtLeastFor:**
```java
@SchedulerLock(
    name = "report-generator",
    lockAtMostFor  = "25m",  // auto-release if crash
    lockAtLeastFor = "20m"   // hold lock for 20 min minimum
)
@Scheduled(fixedRate = 10 * 60 * 1000)  // every 10 minutes
public void generateReports() { ... }
// If job takes 15 min, lockAtLeastFor=20m means next fire at 10min is skipped
```

**Fix 2 — `@Scheduled(fixedDelay)` instead of `fixedRate`:**
```java
// fixedRate: fires every 10 min regardless of how long last run took
@Scheduled(fixedRate = 10 * 60 * 1000)
void badJob() { ... }

// fixedDelay: waits 10 min AFTER the previous run COMPLETES
@Scheduled(fixedDelay = 10 * 60 * 1000)
void goodJob() { ... }
// If job takes 15 min, next run starts at 15+10=25 min — no overlap possible
```

**Fix 3 — Atomic flag to skip if already running:**
```java
private final AtomicBoolean isRunning = new AtomicBoolean(false);

@Scheduled(fixedRate = 60000)
public void job() {
    if (!isRunning.compareAndSet(false, true)) {
        log.info("Job still running — skipping this fire");
        return;
    }
    try {
        doWork();
    } finally {
        isRunning.set(false);
    }
}
```

Note: the AtomicBoolean approach only works within a SINGLE JVM. Across multiple instances, use ShedLock.

**Problem**: Your billing job silently fails at 2 AM. No one knows until customers complain at 9 AM.

**Approach 1 — Heartbeat/Deadman switch with Prometheus:**
```java
