## Option 2: Simple in-house flag system (for getting started)

```java
// Feature flag stored in DB — editable via admin UI
@Entity
@Table(name = "feature_flags")
public class FeatureFlag {
    @Id
    private String name;
    private boolean enabled;
    private int rolloutPercentage;  // 0-100
    private String targetUserIds;   // comma-separated list or null
    private String enabledCountries; // comma-separated or null
}

@Service
@RequiredArgsConstructor
@Slf4j
public class FeatureFlagService {

    private final FeatureFlagRepository repo;

    @Cacheable(value = "feature-flags", key = "#flagName")
    public boolean isEnabled(String flagName, Long userId) {
        FeatureFlag flag = repo.findById(flagName).orElse(null);
        if (flag == null || !flag.isEnabled()) return false;

        // Specific user targeting
        if (flag.getTargetUserIds() != null) {
            return Arrays.asList(flag.getTargetUserIds().split(","))
                .contains(userId.toString());
        }

        // Percentage rollout — deterministic by userId (consistent for same user)
        if (flag.getRolloutPercentage() > 0) {
            // userId % 100 gives a consistent 0-99 bucket for this user
            return (userId % 100) < flag.getRolloutPercentage();
        }

        return true;  // flag enabled, no targeting
    }

    @CacheEvict(value = "feature-flags", key = "#flagName")
    public void updateFlag(String flagName, boolean enabled, int percentage) {
        FeatureFlag flag = repo.findById(flagName).orElse(new FeatureFlag(flagName));
        flag.setEnabled(enabled);
        flag.setRolloutPercentage(percentage);
        repo.save(flag);
        log.info("Feature flag '{}' updated: enabled={}, percentage={}",
            flagName, enabled, percentage);
    }
}
```

**Why `userId % 100` for percentage rollout:**
```text
User ID 1234: 1234 % 100 = 34 → see new feature if rollout >= 35%
User ID 5678: 5678 % 100 = 78 → see new feature if rollout >= 79%
User ID 9100: 9100 % 100 = 0  → always in first 1%

Same user ALWAYS gets the same experience (deterministic)
No Redis/DB needed per-request — just math
```

