## Why HTTP polling doesn't scale

```text
Polling: client asks "has order status changed?" every 5 seconds
  10,000 users × 1 request/5s = 2000 requests/second just for polling
  99% of those return "no change" — wasted work

WebSocket: server PUSHES update only when order status changes
  10,000 open connections — much less CPU/bandwidth than 2000 req/sec polling
```

---

## Step 1: Spring WebSocket with STOMP

```xml
<dependency>
  <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
  <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-websocket</artifactId>
</dependency>
```

```java
@Configuration
@EnableWebSocketMessageBroker
public class WebSocketConfig implements WebSocketMessageBrokerConfigurer {

    @Override
    public void configureMessageBroker(MessageBrokerRegistry registry) {
        // Client subscribes to /topic/... and /user/queue/...
        registry.enableSimpleBroker("/topic", "/queue");

        // Client sends messages to /app/... (if client needs to send to server)
        registry.setApplicationDestinationPrefixes("/app");

        // /user/queue/orders → only sent to specific user, not broadcast
        registry.setUserDestinationPrefix("/user");
    }

    @Override
    public void registerStompEndpoints(StompEndpointRegistry registry) {
        registry.addEndpoint("/ws")
            .setAllowedOriginPatterns("*")
            .withSockJS();  // SockJS fallback for browsers without WebSocket support
    }
}
```

**STOMP concepts:**
```text
/topic/global-updates  → broadcast to ALL subscribers (e.g., public price updates)
/user/{userId}/queue/orders → delivered only to user with that userId
```

---

## Step 2: JWT authentication for WebSocket connection

```java
@Component
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class WebSocketAuthInterceptor implements HandshakeInterceptor {

    private final JwtService jwtService;

    @Override
    public boolean beforeHandshake(ServerHttpRequest request,
            ServerHttpResponse response,
            WebSocketHandler wsHandler, Map<String, Object> attributes) throws Exception {

        // Extract JWT from query param or header
        // (WebSocket upgrade request can't use Authorization header easily)
        String query = request.getURI().getQuery();
        String token = extractToken(query);  // ?token=Bearer.xyz

        if (token == null) {
            response.setStatusCode(HttpStatus.UNAUTHORIZED);
            return false;
        }

        try {
            Claims claims = jwtService.validateToken(token, false);
            attributes.put("userId", claims.getSubject());
            return true;
        } catch (Exception e) {
            response.setStatusCode(HttpStatus.UNAUTHORIZED);
            return false;
        }
    }

    @Override
    public void afterHandshake(...) {}
}
```

---

## Step 3: Push order status updates to specific user

```java
@Service
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class OrderUpdatePusher {

    private final SimpMessagingTemplate messagingTemplate;

    // Called when an order status changes (from Kafka consumer or service call)
    public void pushOrderUpdate(String userId, OrderStatusUpdate update) {
        // /user/{userId}/queue/order-updates
        // Only delivered to WebSocket sessions authenticated as this userId
        messagingTemplate.convertAndSendToUser(
            userId,
            "/queue/order-updates",
            update
        );

        log.info("Pushed order update to user {}: order={} status={}",
            userId, update.getOrderId(), update.getStatus());
    }
}
```

