## Your interview answer

> "I used Spring WebSocket with STOMP. The client connects to /ws (with SockJS fallback for older browsers), authenticates via JWT in the query parameter, and subscribes to /user/queue/order-updates. When a Kafka consumer receives an order-status-changed event, it calls messagingTemplate.convertAndSendToUser() to push the update. The multi-pod problem is solved by using a Redis STOMP broker relay instead of the in-memory broker — all pods publish to Redis, and the pod holding the user's session delivers it. Heartbeat keeps dead connections from accumulating."

