## Alternative: Server-Sent Events (simpler, one-way)

If you only need server → client (no client → server messages):

```java
@GetMapping(value = "/api/orders/{orderId}/events",
            produces = MediaType.TEXT_EVENT_STREAM_VALUE)
public SseEmitter orderStatusStream(
        @PathVariable Long orderId,
        @AuthenticationPrincipal UserDetails user) {

    SseEmitter emitter = new SseEmitter(Long.MAX_VALUE);
    sseManager.register(orderId, user.getUsername(), emitter);

    emitter.onCompletion(() -> sseManager.remove(orderId, user.getUsername()));
    emitter.onTimeout(() -> sseManager.remove(orderId, user.getUsername()));

    return emitter;
}

// Push update
public void pushUpdate(Long orderId, OrderStatusUpdate update) {
    SseEmitter emitter = sseManager.get(orderId);
    if (emitter != null) {
        emitter.send(SseEmitter.event().name("status").data(update));
    }
}
```

SSE is simpler (HTTP, not WebSocket), auto-reconnects, works through HTTP/2 multiplexing. Use SSE for one-way feeds (order status, live logs, progress bars).

